04023nam a22005055i 9780226096056DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013022932  a9780226096056  a(DE-B1597)549940  a(OCoLC)871043376  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHS447.I8bM345 2014 4aHS447.I8b.M345 2014 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a366/.108209452231 aMahmud, Lilith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Brotherhood of Freemason Sisters :bGender, Secrecy, and Fraternity in Italian Masonic Lodges /cLilith Mahmud. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b1 halftone  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction to the Path -- t1. Spaces of Discretion -- t2. Initiations -- t3. Brotherly Love -- t4. Speculative Labor -- t5. Transparent Conspiracies -- tCoda: A Profanation -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom its traces in cryptic images on the dollar bill to Dan Brown’s The Lost Symbol, Freemasonry has long been one of the most romanticized secret societies in the world. But a simple fact escapes most depictions of this elite brotherhood: There are women Freemasons, too. In this groundbreaking ethnography, Lilith Mahmud takes readers inside Masonic lodges in contemporary Italy, where she observes the many ritualistic and fraternal bonds forged among women initiates of this elite and esoteric society. Offering a tantalizing look behind lodge doors, The Brotherhood of Freemason Sisters unveils a complex culture of discretion in which Freemasons simultaneously reveal some truths and hide others. Women—one of Freemasonry’s best-kept secrets—are often upper class and highly educated but paradoxically antifeminist, and their self-cultivation through the Masonic path is an effort to embrace the deeply gendered ideals of fraternity. Mahmud unravels this contradiction at the heart of Freemasonry: how it was at once responsible for many of the egalitarian concepts of the Enlightenment and yet has always been, and in Italy still remains, extremely exclusive. The result is not only a thrilling look at an unfamiliar—and surprisingly influential—world, but a reevaluation altogether of the modern values and ideals that we now take for granted.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFreemasons -- Italy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  afreemason, brotherhood, dan brown, secret societies, women, gender, ethnography, masonic lodge, italy, sisterhood, discretion, egalitarian, elite, enlightenment, initiation, nonfiction, history, sociology, feminism, secrecy, class, race, whiteness, humanism, power, fraternity, anthropology, masons, conservatism, culture, exclusivity, exclusion, discrimination, bias, belonging, insiders.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226096056423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226096056/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles